Hi Ilia

I'm not sure the version of the AIC or StealthAudit is likely to be the problem and it may not be a problem, it might be how its designed - which is fine - but some clarity would be good.

StealthAudit = 11.5.0.165
AIC = 11.5.0.103

Since I raised this call I connected my Power BI report that I referenced in Netwrix Support Ticket #413360 and I would suggest this is more accurate.  For example, I can drill down to the particular share or sub-folder and confirm who actually accessed the share on in the screenshot attached to the call rather than the direct child items.

So I would suggest the AIC is showing us who accesses the share and one level down.

Regards

Mark Chambers

ref:_00D7091pB._500Q000CbRYe:ref

Hi Ilia

I have a task in my backlog to upgrade AIC in our production environment to 11.5.0.136 anyway.

When we migrated our test StealthAudit master server from a 2012 server to a new 2022 server we had some issues with the AIC.  It was recommended to upgrade to the latest version.  It didn't fix that issue, it was a problem around port bindings but when it came to migrating our prod Master Server I forgot that we had upgraded test.

However, this does give me an opportunity to validate whether upgrading it fixes the problem but it doesn't I'm afraid.  So maybe its one of those things that will be fixed in 11.6.

So to summarise, there is a bug in AIC 11.5 that shows the top level of the share + the next level.  However, as I have tapped into the SQL database using the table you previously recommended (SA_FSAC_ActivityEventsView) I can see the data in my Power BI report.

If that is an accurate statement, please close the call.

Regards

Mark Chambers
Infrastructure Operations Senior Specialist
Workplace Services and Contact Centre Platforms

Hi Ilia

 

I have a task in my backlog to upgrade AIC in our production environment to 11.5.0.136 anyway.

 

When we migrated our test StealthAudit master server from a 2012 server to a new 2022 server we had some issues with the AIC.  It was recommended to upgrade to the latest version.  It didn’t fix that issue, it was a problem around port bindings but when it came to migrating our prod Master Server I forgot that we had upgraded test.

 

However, this does give me an opportunity to validate whether upgrading it fixes the problem but it doesn’t I’m afraid.  So maybe its one of those things that will be fixed in 11.6.

 

So to summarise, there is a bug in AIC 11.5 that shows the top level of the share + the next level.  However, as I have tapped into the SQL database using the table you previously recommended (SA_FSAC_ActivityEventsView) I can see the data in my Power BI report.

 

If that is an accurate statement, please close the call.

 

Regards
